'''Funware''', a term coined by [[Gabe Zichermann]],<ref name="funware">{{cite news|publisher=venturebeat|title=Funware’s threat to the traditional video game industry|first=Dean|last=Takahashi|date=May 9, 2008|url=https://venturebeat.com/2008/05/09/funwares-threat-to-the-traditional-video-game-industry/}}</ref><ref name="InventorSpot">{{cite news|publisher=InventorSpot|title=Funware, A New Game Theory For Marketers|first=Ron|last=Callari|date=June 22, 2009|url=http://inventorspot.com/articles/funware_new_game_theory_marketers_28628}}</ref><ref name="venturebeat">{{cite news|publisher=venturebeat|title=Game-based marketing takes off from frequent flyer programs to social media|first=Dean|last=Takahashi|date=March 30, 2010|url=https://venturebeat.com/2010/03/30/game-based-marketing-takes-off-from-frequent-flyer-programs-to-social-media/}}</ref> is the use of [[game mechanics]] in non-game contexts to encourage desired user actions and generate customer loyalty. Funware typically employs [[game mechanics]] such as points, leaderboards, badges, challenges and levels.
Funware is employed online in websites such as [[eBay]] and [[Facebook]]<ref name="worldsin">{{cite news|publisher=Worlds In Motion|title=Funware: Gaming the Web|first=Leigh|last=Alexander |date=February 18, 2008|url=http://www.worldsinmotion.biz/2008/02/funware_gaming_the_web.php}}</ref> as well as in [[application software]] such as ''[[MyTown (video game)|MyTown]]'' and offline activities such as the accumulation of points and leveling up in [[frequent flyer programs]].<ref name="techcrunch">{{cite news|publisher=TechCrunch|title=How To Make Facebook, FedEx, And Amazon More Fun|first=Gabe|last=Zichermann|date=May 27, 2010|url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/03/27/facebook-fedex-amazon-fun/}}</ref> Websites increasingly use [[gamification]] software services such as [http://code.google.com/p/userinfuser UserInfuser] to increase user engagement.
