[[File:Ubisoft Toronto - 2013.jpg|thumb|right|Exterior of Ubisoft Toronto's headquarters]]

'''Ubisoft Toronto Inc.''' is a Canadian [[video game developer]] and a [[subsidiary]] of [[Ubisoft]] based in [[Toronto, Ontario]]. The studio was announced on 6 July 2009, with the [[government of Ontario]] pledging $260&nbsp;million to Ubisoft to create 800 new jobs in the Ontario region.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://kotaku.com/5308480/ubisoft-toronto-brings-800-jobs-to-ontario |title=Ubisoft Toronto Brings 800 Jobs To Ontario |first=Mike |last=Fahey |date=6 July 2009 |website=[[Kotaku]] |accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> The studio's location was confirmed on 4 December 2009.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}

Led by ''[[Assassin's Creed]]'' producer [[Jade Raymond]], the studio developed ''[[Tom Clancy's Splinter Cell: Blacklist]]'', the most recent instalment of the ''[[Tom Clancy's Splinter Cell|Splinter Cell]]'' series, in conjunction with [[Ubisoft Montreal]]. In November 2011, it was revealed that the studio would be supporting the development of the new ''[[Rainbow Six]]'' game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ubisoft Press Release - TERRORISM HITS HOME IN TOM CLANCY'S RAINBOW 6® PATRIOTS VIDEO GAME FROM UBISOFT® |url=http://pressextranet.ubisoft.com/US/US/PublicPages/PressReleasesDetails.aspx?prid=403&title=TERRORISM+HITS+HOME+IN+TOM+CLANCY%E2%80%99S+RAINBOW+6%C2%AE+PATRIOTS+VIDEO+GAME+FROM+UBISOFT%C2%AE |date=3 November 2011 |accessdate=9 November 2011}}</ref>

In July 2015, Ubisoft Toronto announced that they were developing a new [[AAA (video game industry)|AAA]]-level [[intellectual property]] (IP).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/07/14/ubisoft-toronto-is-working-on-a-new-aaa-ip |title=Ubisoft Toronto is Working on a New AAA IP |first=Cassidee |last=Moser |date=14 July 2015 |website=[[IGN]] |accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> At Ubisoft's [[press conference]] at the June 2017 [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]], this IP was revealed to be ''[[Starlink: Battle for Atlas]]'' and [[action-adventure game]] with optional [[toys-to-life]] integration.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/06/12/ubisoft-unveils-starlink-video-game-with-toys-that-attach-to-your-controller/ |title=Ubisoft unveils Starlink video game with toys that attach to your controller |first=Dean |last=Takahashi |date=12 June 2017 |website=[[Venture Beat]] |accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref> Due for late 2018, ''Starlink'' will be the first original IP developed by Ubisoft Toronto.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-06-12-ubisoft-toronto-we-can-bring-life-back-to-toys-to-life |title=Ubisoft Toronto: "We can bring life back to toys-to-life" |first=Christopher |last=Dring |date=12 June 2017 |website=[[GamesIndustry.biz]] |accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>

